This was after connecting and disconnecting a motor controller that was blinking yellow. Then the rest after it in the chain also started to blink yellow.

At no point have we been able to USB connect to a spark Max and get a connection to the rest in the chain all season long. Just the ones we USB-C to. The rest are essentially hidden at all times making me suspect a CAN fault or a faulty controller but checking over the wires myself I didn’t see a green to yellow or a disconnected or bad JST. I’ll triple check again though

That worries me but didn’t seem to affect running at Kettering 2 despite the lack of the chain in the Rev Hardware Client then as well

This really does sound like a CAN wiring issue then. You might want to try swapping things around to isolate the fault, wiggling things while watching the H/W client, or just replacing the segment of wire where things go bad. You could also unplug the SPARK MAX that’s the first not to be seen. Be sure you have the SPARK MAX CAN wires that include the small yellow and green jumper wires.

just to second what the others have said, ive had this issue a few times before and each time it was due to a CAN connection being backwards (H-L, L-H), mostly due to me forgetting that this isnt UART. its also possible that one of the spark max CAN harnesses are damaged, or one of the pins is broken. also verify that none of the dupont pins are bent into the middle slot or outside of the connection entirely.

Draw a picture of your CAN network, with the IDs of all of the SPARK MAXes. Plug into each, confirm it has the right (and unique) CAN ID, and note what other devices you see when plugged directly into that SPARK MAX. If you have a good idea of where the problem lies, you can just do this with one or two SPARK MAXes closest to the problem, on both sides.

It should be pretty obvious from the picture. If you have the ability to unplug things on your CAN bus easily, you can also just unplug everything and add devices on one at a time. The idea is to keep your CAN bus working as you add in SPARK MAXes, until it doesn’t and you know where the problem lies – there could also be more than one problem.

Usually, the roboRIO is on one end of the bus, and the PDH is on the other. You start with these two ends and a single SPARK MAX in the middle, then add more, one at a time. You can also rig up a 120Ω resistor to plug onto the end, as you move the end down.
